class BaseParse(Gst.Element):
    """
    This base class is for parser elements that process data and splits it
    into separate audio/video/whatever frames.

    It provides for:

      * provides one sink pad and one source pad
      * handles state changes
      * can operate in pull mode or push mode
      * handles seeking in both modes
      * handles events (SEGMENT/EOS/FLUSH)
      * handles queries (POSITION/DURATION/SEEKING/FORMAT/CONVERT)
      * handles flushing

    The purpose of this base class is to provide the basic functionality of
    a parser and share a lot of rather complex code.

    # Description of the parsing mechanism:

    ## Set-up phase

     * :class:`GstBase.BaseParse` calls :class:`GstBase.BaseParseClass`::start to inform subclass
       that data processing is about to start now.

     * :class:`GstBase.BaseParse` class calls :class:`GstBase.BaseParseClass`::set_sink_caps to
       inform the subclass about incoming sinkpad caps. Subclass could
       already set the srcpad caps accordingly, but this might be delayed
       until calling :meth:`GstBase.BaseParse.finish_frame` with a non-queued frame.

     * At least at this point subclass needs to tell the :class:`GstBase.BaseParse` class
       how big data chunks it wants to receive (minimum frame size ). It can
       do this with :meth:`GstBase.BaseParse.set_min_frame_size`.

     * :class:`GstBase.BaseParse` class sets up appropriate data passing mode (pull/push)
       and starts to process the data.

    ## Parsing phase

     * :class:`GstBase.BaseParse` gathers at least min_frame_size bytes of data either
       by pulling it from upstream or collecting buffers in an internal
       :class:`GstBase.Adapter`.

     * A buffer of (at least) min_frame_size bytes is passed to subclass
       with :class:`GstBase.BaseParseClass`::handle_frame. Subclass checks the contents
       and can optionally return :class:`GST_FLOW_OK` along with an amount of data
       to be skipped to find a valid frame (which will result in a
       subsequent DISCONT).  If, otherwise, the buffer does not hold a
       complete frame, :class:`GstBase.BaseParseClass`::handle_frame can merely return
       and will be called again when additional data is available.  In push
       mode this amounts to an additional input buffer (thus minimal
       additional latency), in pull mode this amounts to some arbitrary
       reasonable buffer size increase.

       Of course, :meth:`GstBase.BaseParse.set_min_frame_size` could also be used if
       a very specific known amount of additional data is required.  If,
       however, the buffer holds a complete valid frame, it can pass the
       size of this frame to :meth:`GstBase.BaseParse.finish_frame`.

       If acting as a converter, it can also merely indicate consumed input
       data while simultaneously providing custom output data.  Note that
       baseclass performs some processing (such as tracking overall consumed
       data rate versus duration) for each finished frame, but other state
       is only updated upon each call to :class:`GstBase.BaseParseClass`::handle_frame
       (such as tracking upstream input timestamp).

       Subclass is also responsible for setting the buffer metadata
       (e.g. buffer timestamp and duration, or keyframe if applicable).
       (although the latter can also be done by :class:`GstBase.BaseParse` if it is
       appropriately configured, see below).  Frame is provided with
       timestamp derived from upstream (as much as generally possible),
       duration obtained from configuration (see below), and offset
       if meaningful (in pull mode).

       Note that :class:`GstBase.BaseParseClass`::handle_frame might receive any small
       amount of input data when leftover data is being drained (e.g. at
       EOS).

     * As part of finish frame processing, just prior to actually pushing
       the buffer in question, it is passed to
       :class:`GstBase.BaseParseClass`::pre_push_frame which gives subclass yet one last
       chance to examine buffer metadata, or to send some custom (tag)
       events, or to perform custom (segment) filtering.

     * During the parsing process :class:`GstBase.BaseParseClass` will handle both srcpad
       and sinkpad events. They will be passed to subclass if
       :class:`GstBase.BaseParseClass`::sink_event or :class:`GstBase.BaseParseClass`::src_event
       implementations have been provided.

    ## Shutdown phase

    * :class:`GstBase.BaseParse` class calls :class:`GstBase.BaseParseClass`::stop to inform the
      subclass that data parsing will be stopped.

    Subclass is responsible for providing pad template caps for source and
    sink pads. The pads need to be named "sink" and "src". It also needs to
    set the fixed caps on srcpad, when the format is ensured (e.g.  when
    base class calls subclass' :class:`GstBase.BaseParseClass`::set_sink_caps function).

    This base class uses ``GST_FORMAT_DEFAULT`` as a meaning of frames. So,
    subclass conversion routine needs to know that conversion from
    ``GST_FORMAT_TIME`` to ``GST_FORMAT_DEFAULT`` must return the
    frame number that can be found from the given byte position.

    :class:`GstBase.BaseParse` uses subclasses conversion methods also for seeking (or
    otherwise uses its own default one, see also below).

    Subclass ``start`` and ``stop`` functions will be called to inform the beginning
    and end of data processing.

    Things that subclass need to take care of:

    * Provide pad templates
    * Fixate the source pad caps when appropriate
    * Inform base class how big data chunks should be retrieved. This is
      done with :meth:`GstBase.BaseParse.set_min_frame_size` function.
    * Examine data chunks passed to subclass with
      :class:`GstBase.BaseParseClass`::handle_frame and pass proper frame(s) to
      :meth:`GstBase.BaseParse.finish_frame`, and setting src pad caps and timestamps
      on frame.
    * Provide conversion functions
    * Update the duration information with :meth:`GstBase.BaseParse.set_duration`
    * Optionally passthrough using :meth:`GstBase.BaseParse.set_passthrough`
    * Configure various baseparse parameters using
      :meth:`GstBase.BaseParse.set_average_bitrate`, :meth:`GstBase.BaseParse.set_syncable`
      and :meth:`GstBase.BaseParse.set_frame_rate`.

    * In particular, if subclass is unable to determine a duration, but
      parsing (or specs) yields a frames per seconds rate, then this can be
      provided to :class:`GstBase.BaseParse` to enable it to cater for buffer time
      metadata (which will be taken from upstream as much as
      possible). Internally keeping track of frame durations and respective
      sizes that have been pushed provides :class:`GstBase.BaseParse` with an estimated
      bitrate. A default :class:`GstBase.BaseParseClass`::convert (used if not
      overridden) will then use these rates to perform obvious conversions.
      These rates are also used to update (estimated) duration at regular
      frame intervals.
    """
    gimeta: ClassVar[_GIMeta]
    disable_clip: bool
    disable_passthrough: bool
    def __init__(self, *, disable_clip: bool = ..., disable_passthrough: bool = ..., **kwargs: Any) -> None: ...
    def add_index_entry(self, offset: int, ts: Gst.ClockTime, key: bool, force: bool) -> bool:
        """
        Adds an entry to the index associating ``offset`` to ``ts``.  It is recommended
        to only add keyframe entries.  ``force`` allows to bypass checks, such as
        whether the stream is (upstream) seekable, another entry is already "close"
        to the new entry, etc.
        """
    def convert_default(self, src_format: Gst.Format | int, src_value: int, dest_format: Gst.Format | int) -> tuple[bool, int]:
        """
        Default implementation of :class:`GstBase.BaseParseClass`::convert.
        """
    def drain(self) -> None:
